is father Theodore Dwight Woolsey remarried Sarah Sears Prichard two years later in 1854."},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"children_ids":["HD04892","HD04898"],"marriage_number":1}],"education":[{"school_name":"Yale College","institution_id":"INST022","degree_or_field":"A.B.","class_year":1872,"notes":"Yale 1872 — initiate of Skull and Bones senior society same year."},{"school_name":"Yale Law School","institution_id":"INST022","degree_or_field":"LL.B.","class_year":1876,"notes":"Yale Law 1876."}],"career":[{"role":"Instructor in Public Law","organization":"Yale College","location":"New Haven, CT","start_year":1877,"end_year":1878,"institution_id":"INST022"},{"role":"Professor of International Law","organization":"Yale University","location":"New Haven, CT","start_year":1878,"end_year":1911,"notes":"33 years as Yale's Professor of International Law. Retired 1911.","institution_id":"INST022"},{"role":"Founding editor","organization":"Yale Review","location":"New Haven, CT","notes":"One of the founders of the Yale Review and a frequent contributor."}],"military_service":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST022","relationship":"alumnus"},{"institution_id":"INST068"}],"landmarks":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"artworks":[],"tags":["yale_graduate","academic","lawyer","skull_and_bones","author"],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"education","header":"Yale 1872 with Skull and Bones, then Law","body":"He graduated Yale College in 1872 — the same year he was initiated into Skull and Bones — and took his Bachelor of Laws at Yale Law School in 1876. He traveled in Europe before becoming Instructor in Public Law at Yale in 1877."},{"number":2,"category":"career","header":"Thirty-three years as Yale International Law professor","body":"From 1878 to 1911 he held Yale's Professor of International Law chair — thirty-three years. As his memorialist Charles Cheney Hyde wrote, for the first twenty years 'interest in the law of nations was not widespread or intense in America' and Woolsey 'was doing spade work, preparing the ground in his own land for the seeds there later sown.'"},{"number":3,"category":"literature","header":"Edited father's textbook, founded Yale Review","body":"In 1891 he published the sixth edition of his father's influential 'An Introduction to the Study of International Law' — reprinted 1901 and 1906. He was a founder of the Yale Review journal and authored 'America's Foreign Policy' (1898)."},{"number":4,"category":"family","header":"Mother died twelve days after his birth","body":"Born to Yale president Theodore Dwight Woolsey and Martha Salisbury Woolsey on 22 October 1852, he lost his mother on 3 November 1852 — only twelve days later. His father remarried Sarah Sears Prichard two years afterward and had four more children with her."}],"quotes":[],"sources":[{"label":"Wikipedia — Theodore Salisbury Woolsey","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Theodore_Salisbury_Woolsey"},{"label":"Charles Cheney Hyde 1929 memorial — American Journal of International Law"}],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"slug":"theodore-woolsey-1852"}},"burialCemetery":null,"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}